  <section class="about-section animate-on-scroll" id="about">
    <div class="about-container">
      <div class="about-content">
        <h2 class="about-title animate-fade-up">My Journey to Authenticity</h2>

        <p class="about-text animate-fade-up" style="animation-delay: 0.1s;">
          For much of my life, I lived in survival mode — constantly doing,
          managing, and holding things together. I was capable, responsible, and
          dependable, yet internally I felt anxious and overwhelmed, under quiet
          but relentless pressure. I didn’t yet realize how much of my life was
          being driven by effort rather than alignment, by survival rather than
          presence.
        </p>

        <p class="about-text animate-fade-up" style="animation-delay: 0.2s;">
          That quiet undercurrent stayed with me into adulthood, even as I
          pursued my Master’s in Social Work, got married, and began building a
          family. From the outside, I was fully functioning and progressing —
          professionally and personally. I was capable, productive, and
          responsible. And yet internally, I felt anxious, insecure, and
          detached, unsure why life felt so flat despite everything I had built.
          I kept moving forward, hoping that the next milestone would bring a
          sense of arrival, without realizing that I was still disconnected from
          parts of myself that had never been given space to be felt.
        </p>

        <p class="about-text animate-fade-up" style="animation-delay: 0.3s;">
          Over time, my body began to reflect what I hadn’t yet allowed myself
          to feel — through headaches, neck pain, stiffness, and a general sense
          of tightness. These weren’t problems to solve, but invitations to slow
          down and listen. As I did, it became clear that beneath the
          productivity and strength was a reservoir of unexpressed emotion —
          grief, resentment, fear, and exhaustion — waiting not for effort or
          analysis, but for safety.
        </p>

        <p class="about-text animate-fade-up" style="animation-delay: 0.4s;">
          The healing came through allowing myself to be seen and held in a
          space of safety and love — both through the presence of others and
          through learning how to offer that same kind of witnessing to myself.
          In that kind of presence, what had long been held could begin to move,
          supported and contained. Through this process, I came to understand
          that healing isn’t about fixing what’s wrong with us, but about
          allowing what has been silenced to move, safely and with care — until
          our truth, vitality, and wholeness can be felt again.
        </p>

        <p class="about-text animate-fade-up" style="animation-delay: 0.5s;">
          And with that came something I hadn’t known how to access before:
          flow. A sense of alignment. Moments of real joy and aliveness. Life
          began to move with me rather than against me. There was more ease,
          more presence, and even moments of quiet ecstasy — the deep relief of
          no longer fighting myself.
        </p>

        <p class="about-text animate-fade-up" style="animation-delay: 0.6s;">
          As I moved through this painful and profoundly transformative process,
          a quiet knowing emerged: this journey wasn’t meant to be mine alone. I
          felt called to offer others the kind of space I had received — a place
          where the work between survival and thriving could unfold with care
          and support.
        </p>

        <p class="about-text animate-fade-up" style="animation-delay: 0.7s;">
          Now, as a soul doula, I hold space for those moving through grief,
          burnout, anxiety, and emotional awakening — especially those who
          appear successful on the outside but long for something more real,
          more vibrant, and more aligned within. My work is grounded in the
          wisdom I’ve lived: that true healing happens not when we are fixed,
          but when we are held — with gentleness, love, and the deep remembering
          that we were never broken to begin with.
        </p>

        <p class="about-text animate-fade-up" style="animation-delay: 0.8s;">
          This is the heart of what I offer: soul-deep presence, intuitive
          guidance, and the loving support that allows you to return to your own
          light.
        </p>
      </div>

